==English==
{{wikisource1911Enc|Abdication}}

===Etymology===
{{PIE root|en|deyḱ}}
First attested in 1552. From {{etyl|frm|en}} {{m|frm|abdication}}, from {{etyl|la|en}} {{m|la|abdicātiō||renunciation}}, from {{m|la|abdicō}}<ref>{{R:CDOE|page=2}}</ref>.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|RP}} {{IPA|/ˌæb.dəˈkeɪ.ʃən/|lang=en}}
* {{a|US}} {{IPA|/ˌæb.dəˈkeɪ.ʃən/|lang=en}}
* {{audio|en-us-abdication.ogg|Audio (US)|lang=en}}
* {{rhymes|eɪʃən|lang=en}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun|~}}

# {{lb|en|obsolete}} The act of disowning or disinheriting a child. {{defdate|Attested from the mid 16<sup>th</sup> century until the mid 17<sup>th</sup> century.}}<ref name=SOED>{{R:SOED5|page=3}}</ref>
# The act of [[abdicating]]; the [[renunciation]] of a high office, dignity, or trust, by its [[holder]]. {{defdate|First attested in the early 17<sup>th</sup> century.}}<ref name=SOED/>
# The voluntary renunciation of sovereign power{{defdate|First attested in the late 17<sup>th</sup> century.}}<ref name=SOED/>
#:'''''abdication''' of the throne, government, power, authority''
# {{lb|en|obsolete|legal}} The renunciation of interest in a property or a legal claim; [[abandonment]]. {{defdate|Attested only in the mid 18<sup>th</sup> century.}}<ref name=SOED/>
# {{lb|en|obsolete}} The action of being deposed from the seat of power. {{defdate|Attested only in the mid 17<sup>th</sup> century.}}<ref name=SOED/>

